article.headline: Rose scores 22, grabs 10 boards
article.linkText: Raptors win third straight since trade
article.story:
TORONTO (AP) _ Vince Carter didn't expect the Toronto Raptors' big trade to produce such a quick turnaround. Jalen Rose had 22 points, 10 assists and eight rebounds, and Carter also scored 22 in the new-look Raptors' third straight victory, 92-87 over the Atlanta Hawks on Friday night. Donyell Marshall added 21 points for the Raptors, who are 3-0 since acquiring Rose, Marshall and Lonny Baxter from Chicago. "I knew good things were going to happen, but now it's just like 'Wow'," Carter said. "It's just above and beyond expectations for all of us." Carter, in foul trouble throughout the game, had 12 points in the fourth quarter to help Toronto win its third in a row for the first time this season. Carter believes Raptors fans haven't been this excited in years. "It brings us back to 2000 when we were playing in the playoffs," said Carter, whose team came within a jump shot of making it to the Eastern Conference finals that season. "We're trying to create that atmosphere again." Jason Terry had 19 points for the Hawks, who have lost three straight and five of six. "The Raptors definitely have a much more rounded offense," Shareef Abdur-Rahim said. "You just have took at the box score to see that. Last time it was pretty much Vince carrying the load offensively, but this time you have three guys with 20-plus." Abdur-Rahim added 15 points and 12 rebounds for the Hawks. Terry's jumper over Chris Bosh gave Atlanta an 82-81 lead with 1:52 left. After Rose missed a 3-pointer, Bosh grabbed an offensive rebound and found Marshall wide open for a 3-pointer after he missed his first six attempts. "I wasn't hitting them, but coach told me I was going to hit the big one," Marshall said of first-year Raptors coach Kevin O'Neill. "Soon as I hit it, I looked over to him and he said 'I told you so."' Theo Ratliff tied it with a 12-foot jumper, and Stephen Jackson made one of two free throws to give Atlanta a one-point lead. Carter made two free throws with 40 seconds left to put Toronto ahead for good. After Terry missed a long jumper from the top of the key, Carter grabbed the rebound and made two more free throws. Atlanta's Boris Diaw missed a 3-pointer, and Rose made four free throws in the final 15 seconds to clinch the win. "Jalen almost had a triple-double. That's what he does. He's hard to cover when he plays the point," Marshall said. "We knew we were brought in to score as well as play defense. We're doing a decent job of doing both so far." After setting a franchise record with 17 3-pointers in Wednesday's victory over Boston, the Raptors went 2-for-15 from behind the arc. Toronto won despite being outrebounded for the third straight game, 41-35. "You can classify this game as winning ugly," Rose said. "We got off to a really good start and squandered it early in the first half. Vince got into foul trouble and we just tried to hold on until he got back in the fourth quarter." Marshall scored nine points and Rose had six assists as the Raptors took a 12-point lead in the first quarter. The Hawks committed seven turnovers in the first five minutes, including four by Jackson. Atlanta's Dion Glover, who lost his spot in the starting lineup to Diaw, scored six of his 10 first-half points during a 13-4 run in the second quarter. Diaw capped the run with a dunk, giving Atlanta its first lead.<

Game notes
Asked to recall a more undersized frontcourt than the Raptors', O'Neill said: "We're pretty thin. We're not deep up front right now. An injury to any one of those three guys would be a blow to us." Bosh is 6-foot-10, but weighs just 225. Marshall is 6-foot-9 and is more of a perimeter threat, and Baxter is 6-foot-8. Davis and Williams started in the frontcourt. ... Glover entered the game shooting 35 percent. ... Toronto's mascot, the Raptor, missed the game with a bruised tailbone. ... Glover had 11 points. ... Carter played just 26 minutes.
